    "instructions": [
      {
        "step_number": 1,
        "phase": "prep",
        "text": "Make the 'Sam Kluer' paste: Pound white peppercorns in a mortar until fine. Add coriander roots and garlic cloves, pounding until a smooth, uniform paste forms.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "POUND",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": null,
          "doneness_cues": {
            "visual": "Smooth paste",
            "tactile": "Uniform consistency"
          }
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 2,
        "phase": "cook",
        "text": "Heat 15ml vegetable oil in a wok or saucepan over medium heat. Add the pounded paste and sliced shallots. Sauté until the shallots soften and the mixture is highly aromatic.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "SAUTÉ",
          "temperature": {
            "celsius": 160,
            "fahrenheit": 320
          },
          "duration": "PT3M",
          "doneness_cues": {
            "visual": "Shallots are translucent",
            "tactile": null
          }
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 3,
        "phase": "cook",
        "text": "Add the minced chicken and shrimp to the pan. Stir vigorously to break up any clumps and cook until the meat turns opaque.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "SAUTÉ",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": "PT4M",
          "doneness_cues": {
            "visual": "Meat is opaque",
            "tactile": null
          }
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 4,
        "phase": "cook",
        "text": "Pour in the coconut milk, then season with palm sugar, fish sauce, and tamarind paste. Bring to a gentle simmer. Add the coarsely ground peanuts and stir to combine.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "SIMMER",
          "temperature": {
            "celsius": 90,
            "fahrenheit": 194
          },
          "duration": "PT10M",
          "doneness_cues": {
            "visual": "Sauce has thickened slightly and turned a rich golden color",
            "tactile": null
          }
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 5,
        "phase": "finish",
        "text": "Reduce heat to low and let the dip simmer gently until it reaches a coating consistency. Taste and adjust seasoning; it should be predominantly sweet and salty with a hint of nutty richness. Remove from heat.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "REDUCE",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": "PT5M",
          "doneness_cues": {
            "visual": null,
            "tactile": "Coats the back of a spoon"
          }
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 6,
        "phase": "cook",
        "text": "Clean the wok or use a separate pot. Heat frying oil to 190°C/375°F. Fry the dried rice cakes in batches. They will expand instantly. Flip once and remove immediately (within 5-10 seconds) to drain on a wire rack.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "FRY",
          "temperature": {
            "celsius": 190,
            "fahrenheit": 374
          },
          "duration": null,
          "doneness_cues": {
            "visual": "Puffed, white, and crispy",
            "tactile": null
          }
        },
        "tips": [
          "Do not overcrowd the oil; the crackers expand significantly."
        ]
      },
      {
        "step_number": 7,
        "phase": "assemble",
        "text": "Transfer the warm dip to a serving bowl. Garnish with sliced red spur chilies and coriander leaves. Serve alongside the crispy rice crackers for dipping.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "SERVE",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": null,
          "doneness_cues": null
        },
        "tips": []
      }
    ],
    "troubleshooting": [
      {
        "symptom": "Rice crackers are tough or hard, not airy",
        "likely_cause": "Oil temperature was too low",
        "prevention": "Ensure oil reaches 190°C/375°F before adding dried rice cakes",
        "fix": "Heat oil properly and try again with a test piece; cannot fix already fried crackers"
      },
      {
        "symptom": "Dip is too thin/watery",
        "likely_cause": "Coconut milk was low fat or sauce wasn't reduced enough",
        "prevention": "Use full-fat coconut milk",
        "fix": "Simmer longer to evaporate moisture, or add more ground peanuts to thicken"
      }
    ],
    "chef_notes": [
      "The foundation of Thai flavor is the 'Sam Kluer' (Three Buddies): coriander root, garlic, and white pepper. Do not skip the white pepper; black pepper changes the flavor profile entirely.",
      "If you cannot find dried rice cakes (raw khao tang), you can dehydrate cooked jasmine rice in a low oven (80°C) for 3-4 hours until rock hard before frying.",
      "Roast raw peanuts yourself in a dry pan before grinding for a vastly superior aroma compared to pre-roasted store-bought peanuts.",
      "The consistency of the dip should be similar to a Bolognese sauce—thick enough to sit on top of the cracker without running off immediately."
    ],
    "cultural_context": "Khao Tang Na Tang is a traditional Royal Thai appetizer dating back to the Ayutthaya period. Originally a way to use leftover rice (sun-dried to preserve it), it was elevated with a rich, coconut-based dipping sauce ('Na Tang') often reserved for guests and ceremonies. The balance of salty, sweet, and nutty flavors represents the harmony sought in central Thai cuisine.",
